{{refimprove|date=January 2014}} {{Italic title|reason=[[:Category:German words and phrases]]}} {{Nazism sidebar}} [[File:Nur fur deutsche.jpg|thumb|"Only for German Passengers" on tram route 8, car no. 94 in occupied [[Kraków]].]] [[File:Napis na latarni 'Nur fur Deutsche'.png|thumb|right|''Nur für Deutsche'' graffiti on the base of a lamppost in occupied Poland]] The slogan '''''Nur für Deutsche''''' ([[English language|English]]: "Only for [[german people|German]]s") was during [[World War II]], in many German-occupied countries, a [[Racism|racialist]] slogan indicating that certain establishments and transportation were reserved for Germans. Signs bearing the slogan were posted at entrances to parks, cafes, cinemas, theaters and other facilities.
==History==
In [[occupation of Poland|German-occupied Poland]], [[racial segregation]] was nearly complete. In streetcars and trains, the first car was usually reserved for German administrative and military personnel, Nazi party members, and German civilians. Other nationalities were to use the remaining car(s).
In [[Polish partisans|Polish partisan]] parlance, toxic or otherwise undrinkable [[moonshine]] was jocularly called "nur für Deutsche".
Partisans were also fond of painting the words "nur für Deutsche" on graveyard fences or street lampposts (a reference to [[hanging]]).<ref>[http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:hoWXZoLf9DwJ:archiwum.wiz.pl/1999/99092700.asp&hl=pl&ct=clnk&cd=3&gl=pl "OKUPACYJNA CODZIENNOŚĆ"], by KATARZYNA GRACZYKOWSKA, (also in [http://archiwum.wiz.pl/1999/99092700.asp the archive] of ''Wiedza i Życie'' no. 9, 1999)</ref>
